ted cormorant in the twenty-first century. Conservation biologist Linda Wires provides a unique synthesis of the cultural, historical, scientific, and political elements of the cormorant’s story. She discusses the amazing late-twentieth-century population recovery, aided by protection policies and environment conservation, but also the subsequent U.S. federal policies under which hundreds of thousands of the birds have been killed. In a critique of the science, management, and ethics underlying the double-crested cormorant’s treatment today, Wires exposes “management” as a euphemism for persecution and shows that the current strategies of aggressive predator control are outdated and unsupported by science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBird pestszNorth America. 0aDouble-crested cormorantxEconomic aspectszNorth America. 0aDouble-crested cormorantzNorth America. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszNorth America. 70(DE-601)1046167170(DE-588)4063737-2aVogelschutz2gnd 70(DE-601)2274842070(DE-588)4453264-7aFischereischaden2gnd 70(DE-601)7006126020(DE-588)7727386-2aKormoranegFamilie2gnd 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Ornithology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030018711340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018826440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300188264423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300188264/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY